1
00:00:44,886 --> 00:00:46,911
Excited, Pete?

2
00:00:47,221 --> 00:00:49,155
About what?

3
00:00:49,324 --> 00:00:51,189
Aboput the fact that you
are going to be...

4
00:00:51,359 --> 00:00:54,055
...uno de los hombres más 
importantes del pais esta noche.

5
00:00:55,396 --> 00:00:57,125
- ¿Piensas eso?
- ¿Piensas eso?

6
00:00:57,298 --> 00:00:59,960
After 25 years ruling
the underworld...

7
00:01:00,134 --> 00:01:03,865
...Benny Costain, el hombre más
poderoso y temido del pais,...

8
00:01:04,038 --> 00:01:07,633
...será procesado gracias
a Pete Tonelli.

9
00:01:07,809 --> 00:01:10,004
¿Sabe lo que hace Costain...

10
00:01:10,178 --> 00:01:12,237
...a los que intentan delatarle?

11
00:01:12,413 --> 00:01:14,506
Después de su testimonio...

12
00:01:14,682 --> 00:01:17,082
...no estará aquí 
para hacer nada, Pete.

13
00:01:17,251 --> 00:01:19,082
Yeah.

14
00:01:19,253 --> 00:01:21,016
Maybe.

15
00:01:22,790 --> 00:01:25,350
Maybe I'm gonna be on the stand.

16
00:01:25,526 --> 00:01:27,084
Why, sure you are, Pete.

17
00:01:27,261 --> 00:01:29,354
You're gonna get on the stand.

18
00:01:29,530 --> 00:01:32,829
And we'll see to it that nothing
happens to you after you do.

19
00:01:33,001 --> 00:01:34,263
We sure will.

20
00:03:24,679 --> 00:03:28,115
Oh, now, look, kid, it isn't so bad.

21
00:03:28,282 --> 00:03:30,273
See if you can't think of this joint...

22
00:03:30,451 --> 00:03:34,080
...as a sort of a training ground
for future life.

23
00:03:34,255 --> 00:03:36,246
Of course, training for what
beats me.

24
00:03:36,424 --> 00:03:39,018
But I've never been in prison before.

25
00:03:40,094 --> 00:03:42,494
Half the time, I don't know
what they're saying.

26
00:03:42,663 --> 00:03:44,756
Because I don't know,
I do something wrong.

27
00:03:44,932 --> 00:03:48,766
- Then they yell at me like I'm stupid.
- Okay, kid, so now you can relax.

28
00:03:48,936 --> 00:03:51,905
You finally got your first break
since they dragged you in.

29
00:03:52,073 --> 00:03:54,405
- Break?
- Certainly, they turned you over to me.

30
00:03:54,575 --> 00:03:58,306
I happen to know more about this joint
than those grafters that built it.

31
00:03:58,479 --> 00:04:00,037
Yeah, but I don't.

32
00:04:00,214 --> 00:04:03,206
Okay, so you don't.
So I'm gonna tell you.

33
00:04:03,384 --> 00:04:07,320
Certain things in the beginning is
more important to know than others.

34
00:04:07,488 --> 00:04:09,979
And other things is
even more important than that.

35
00:04:10,158 --> 00:04:12,888
And one of the most important things
in this place...

36
00:04:13,060 --> 00:04:15,085
...is, don't volunteer for nothing.

37
00:04:15,563 --> 00:04:17,758
- Don't volunteer?
- Now, remember that.

38
00:04:17,932 --> 00:04:21,732
When they come, wagging their tails
and trying to act warm and friendly...

39
00:04:21,903 --> 00:04:25,839
...about some extra work that's gotta
be done, you don't do nothing.

40
00:04:26,007 --> 00:04:28,202
You just sit there,
like a hunk of wet wash.

41
00:04:28,376 --> 00:04:30,606
And don't volunteer.

42
00:04:30,878 --> 00:04:32,140
Why not?

43
00:04:32,313 --> 00:04:34,144
Why should you help the jerks out...

44
00:04:34,315 --> 00:04:37,182
...that's keeping you here,
for one thing?

45
00:04:37,351 --> 00:04:42,687
And don't ever do one bit more than
just exactly what you're told to do.

46
00:04:43,891 --> 00:04:45,518
But how do you get around them?

47
00:04:45,693 --> 00:04:49,185
Okay. Supposing they come to me,
and they say:

48
00:04:49,363 --> 00:04:52,696
"Conley, on this floor,
there's a spot."

49
00:04:52,867 --> 00:04:55,802
Do I go ahead and wet-mop
from here to extremity?

50
00:04:55,970 --> 00:04:57,232
Not you.

51
00:04:58,272 --> 00:05:00,240
Not on your life, I don't.

52
00:05:00,408 --> 00:05:02,342
And I don't go over that floor...

53
00:05:02,510 --> 00:05:05,377
...except just where they point out
it's spotty exactly.

54
00:05:05,546 --> 00:05:08,037
And what do we usually say
about that?

55
00:05:08,216 --> 00:05:11,674
You usually say, "Don't you have
no brains, Conley?

56
00:05:11,853 --> 00:05:14,822
Don't you know we meant
to clean the whole filthy floor?"

57
00:05:14,989 --> 00:05:17,219
That always gives Conley
a chance to say...

58
00:05:17,391 --> 00:05:20,326
"If I had any brains,
what would I be doing in this trap?"

59
00:05:20,494 --> 00:05:22,826
Come on, you're wanted
in the warden's office.

60
00:05:22,997 --> 00:05:24,726
The warden's office?

61
00:05:24,899 --> 00:05:27,993
For what? It's just about time
for the dinner to gong.

62
00:05:28,169 --> 00:05:30,000
Now, don't show off, Conley.

63
00:05:30,171 --> 00:05:31,729
Come on.

64
00:05:31,906 --> 00:05:34,704
Like poor, dumb sheep, we're
moved from barn to stall...

65
00:05:34,876 --> 00:05:36,639
...and nobody tells us why.

66
00:05:36,811 --> 00:05:38,574
It's inhuman.

67
00:05:38,746 --> 00:05:41,408
Don't volunteer for nothing.

68
00:05:41,582 --> 00:05:43,345
This way.

69
00:06:01,969 --> 00:06:03,630
When we're thrown off schedule...

70
00:06:03,804 --> 00:06:06,967
...you can't blame our stomachs
for growling a little.

71
00:06:11,712 --> 00:06:13,145
Hello, Conley.

72
00:06:13,314 --> 00:06:17,045
As I understand it, Conley will
remain in our custody even though...

73
00:06:17,218 --> 00:06:19,914
...you'll take her outside the prison?
- That's right.

74
00:06:20,087 --> 00:06:23,545
- Get her into her street clothes.
- Yes, ma'am.

75
00:06:23,724 --> 00:06:25,123
Anything wrong?

76
00:06:25,293 --> 00:06:27,557
If there was,
I'd be the last one to be told.

77
00:06:27,728 --> 00:06:29,218
That will do, Conley.

78
00:06:29,397 --> 00:06:34,164
I don't suppose it'd do any good if I
ask if my civil rights is being violated.

79
00:06:34,335 --> 00:06:37,463
I have a court order to give you
to the federal authorities.

80
00:06:37,638 --> 00:06:39,902
In an unfed condition?

81
00:06:40,074 --> 00:06:42,668
We won't be long, lieutenant.

82
00:06:49,250 --> 00:06:53,846
This time, the inmate's stomach
is not to be blamed.

83
00:07:05,800 --> 00:07:08,963
Four years of too many potatoes,
Conley.

84
00:07:09,136 --> 00:07:14,301
Potatoes? I thought those were
plastic cotton balls they were testing.

85
00:08:49,837 --> 00:08:51,771
Look out, will you?

86
00:09:07,288 --> 00:09:10,655
Would you mind telling me
what this is all...?

87
00:09:16,297 --> 00:09:18,322
Nobody talks to me.

88
00:09:35,816 --> 00:09:39,843
Well, aren't we the real life-size
Boston Blackies.

89
00:09:46,060 --> 00:09:47,925
Why? Why?

90
00:10:04,678 --> 00:10:06,077
Help yourself.

91
00:10:06,247 --> 00:10:08,010
Thanks.

92
00:10:16,157 --> 00:10:19,092
Hey, look at them new styles!

93
00:10:22,096 --> 00:10:27,432
I guess maybe these old rags of mine
must look like Easter parade in 1902.

94
00:10:27,601 --> 00:10:31,059
Sister, I wouldn't know styles
if you shoved them down my throat.

95
00:10:31,238 --> 00:10:32,500
You're sure of that, huh?

96
00:10:32,673 --> 00:10:35,870
Why? Because you had so many
of them shoved down your throat?

97
00:10:37,044 --> 00:10:40,207
Why is it nobody ever thought
of building a nice, big statue...

98
00:10:40,381 --> 00:10:43,748
...to the first cop who ever called
a girl "sister"?

99
00:10:43,918 --> 00:10:45,943
Because if he hadn't come along...

100
00:10:46,120 --> 00:10:49,578
...the police would sure put on
their bare faces for small talk.

101
00:10:50,224 --> 00:10:53,091
What's it with a cop?
Always gotta call you "sister."

102
00:10:53,260 --> 00:10:54,522
You like "mother" better?

103
00:10:54,695 --> 00:10:57,061
Maybe I'd like my own name
for a change.

104
00:10:57,231 --> 00:11:00,394
- Maybe you would.
- Yeah, try it for size.

105
00:11:05,306 --> 00:11:07,706
Oh, look! Polka dots!

106
00:11:07,875 --> 00:11:10,400
Look at that dress in the window!

107
00:11:12,746 --> 00:11:16,341
I hope you don't object to a person
looking out their own window.

108
00:11:16,517 --> 00:11:19,748
You'll know right away
if I object to anything.

109
00:11:19,920 --> 00:11:22,753
What'll you do, light up?

110
00:12:24,918 --> 00:12:27,785
Would the world collapse
if somebody told me something?

111
00:12:27,955 --> 00:12:29,855
Somebody will.

112
00:12:36,096 --> 00:12:37,529
Clayton.

113
00:12:39,533 --> 00:12:41,091
- Whole floor cleared?
- Yes, sir.

114
00:12:41,268 --> 00:12:44,294
- How about the roof?
- The men are already up there.

115
00:13:20,240 --> 00:13:22,003
What are we gonna have, a party?

116
00:13:23,444 --> 00:13:25,435
What kind of prisoners
do you keep here?

117
00:13:25,612 --> 00:13:28,604
Willoughby, get her settled.
I'll be back in a minute.

118
00:13:30,684 --> 00:13:32,675
You didn't tell her anything?

119
00:13:32,853 --> 00:13:35,686
What about the trip here?
You sure you weren't followed?

120
00:13:35,856 --> 00:13:38,416
I'm sure I was. I lost them.

121
00:13:38,592 --> 00:13:40,856
- You're positive?
- Please.

122
00:13:41,028 --> 00:13:42,393
All right.

123
00:13:42,563 --> 00:13:44,463
What's she like, Vince?

124
00:13:44,631 --> 00:13:47,099
Just like the rest that come
through the lineup.

125
00:13:47,267 --> 00:13:50,759
Smart-talking, brassy,
third-class citizen.

126
00:13:50,938 --> 00:13:52,997
And she's our last chance.

127
00:13:53,173 --> 00:13:56,802
If she doesn't come through,
we'll be thrown out of court Monday...

128
00:13:56,977 --> 00:13:58,706
...and there goes two years' work.

129
00:13:58,879 --> 00:14:03,077
Then she ought to be in the city jail,
where Costain can't knock her off.

130
00:14:03,250 --> 00:14:05,741
Let's do it my way.

131
00:14:13,827 --> 00:14:16,694
- What's so interesting?
- People.

132
00:14:17,231 --> 00:14:18,493
And cars.

133
00:14:18,665 --> 00:14:21,634
But mostly people who can go
anyplace they wanna go.

134
00:14:23,537 --> 00:14:25,835
Haven't seen anybody like that
for four years.

135
00:14:26,006 --> 00:14:28,236
- Who's that?
- My daughter.

136
00:14:28,409 --> 00:14:31,310
- Are you married?
- I was.

137
00:14:33,347 --> 00:14:35,781
He died in France,
in the Normandy landings.

138
00:14:36,917 --> 00:14:39,351
None of us never knew that.

139
00:14:41,255 --> 00:14:44,691
It must scare you to have a daughter
with a job like yours...

140
00:14:44,858 --> 00:14:47,486
...that always points out
what can happen to a girl.

141
00:14:47,661 --> 00:14:50,027
And she's pretty.

142
00:14:52,533 --> 00:14:56,526
Pretty lucky kid to have a mother
like you that's so crazy about her.

143
00:14:56,703 --> 00:15:00,969
Of course, I am crazy about her,
but how did you know?

144
00:15:01,141 --> 00:15:04,008
You should've seen your look
when I said she was pretty.

145
00:15:04,178 --> 00:15:06,476
Willoughby, send her in here.

146
00:15:06,647 --> 00:15:08,615
I guess they want you in there now.

147
00:15:08,782 --> 00:15:10,044
For what?

148
00:15:10,217 --> 00:15:13,983
I don't know any more than you do,
but you'd better go.

149
00:15:21,094 --> 00:15:23,255
You don't, huh?

150
00:15:26,333 --> 00:15:28,665
We arrived at the place
where you'll explain...

151
00:15:28,836 --> 00:15:31,327
...this dragging of a person
from here to there?

152
00:15:31,505 --> 00:15:34,906
Yes, we've finally arrived
at that place, Miss Conley.

153
00:15:35,075 --> 00:15:37,009
Would you please sit down?

154
00:15:39,012 --> 00:15:40,843
My name is Lloyd Hallett.

155
00:15:41,014 --> 00:15:42,845
I'm an attorney for the government.

156
00:15:43,016 --> 00:15:45,041
You mean I'm up
for some kind of tax rap?

157
00:15:45,219 --> 00:15:49,713
No, you're not up for any kind
of raps, so you can just relax.

158
00:15:50,724 --> 00:15:53,022
Would you care for a cigarette?

159
00:15:58,966 --> 00:16:01,230
One for later, after dinner.

160
00:16:01,401 --> 00:16:02,663
Certainly.

161
00:16:02,836 --> 00:16:06,067
We thought you could be helpful
by giving us some information...

162
00:16:06,240 --> 00:16:09,403
...about a case that I'm prosecuting.

163
00:16:09,910 --> 00:16:13,744
Case? What I know about cases,
you can put on the head of a pin.

164
00:16:13,914 --> 00:16:17,008
- Perhaps I can be a bit more explicit.
- You do that.

165
00:16:17,184 --> 00:16:21,086
You used to go around with a man
named Pete Tonelli, didn't you?

166
00:16:21,255 --> 00:16:24,918
Go around? You mean, like
merry-go-rounds and revolving doors?

167
00:16:25,492 --> 00:16:27,983
I mean, you used to be
a friend of Tonelli's.

168
00:16:28,161 --> 00:16:31,653
- Friends, perhaps, but nothing more.
- Miss Conley...

169
00:16:31,832 --> 00:16:35,825
...there's no danger of implicating
yourself by answers you might give.

170
00:16:36,003 --> 00:16:40,064
I'd just like it made clear if Pete's done
anything, he can do his own hanging.

171
00:16:40,240 --> 00:16:43,004
- Well, that point is now on the record.
- That's good.

172
00:16:43,176 --> 00:16:46,612
You took a trip one time with Pete,
didn't you?

173
00:16:47,714 --> 00:16:49,545
It was on a yacht.

174
00:16:49,716 --> 00:16:52,708
And I believe you went
to the West Indies.

175
00:16:52,886 --> 00:16:56,686
- Yacht?
- Yeah, those long, white things.

176
00:16:56,857 --> 00:16:59,018
I know what's a yacht.

177
00:16:59,192 --> 00:17:02,628
Some cops assume because you've
been persecuted falsely all over...

178
00:17:02,796 --> 00:17:04,058
Persecuted falsely?

179
00:17:04,231 --> 00:17:07,394
I'm sure the lieutenant didn't mean
to offend you, Miss Conley.

180
00:17:07,568 --> 00:17:09,160
Excuse me, please.

181
00:17:09,336 --> 00:17:13,830
- Watch how you're kicking my shins.
- Vince, give me a hand.

182
00:17:20,514 --> 00:17:22,675
I thought perhaps you could use
a drink.

183
00:17:22,849 --> 00:17:25,750
Yeah, like some dumb cops
could use some manners.

184
00:17:25,919 --> 00:17:28,114
That much over the flagstones,
Mr. Hallett.

185
00:17:28,522 --> 00:17:32,424
When are you gonna quit asking her
and start telling her for a change?

186
00:17:32,593 --> 00:17:35,187
Would you like to step out
while I'm doing this?

187
00:17:35,362 --> 00:17:37,353
You gonna do it this way? Yeah.

188
00:17:37,531 --> 00:17:39,692
Thanks.

189
00:17:48,742 --> 00:17:50,437
There you are.

190
00:17:50,611 --> 00:17:52,670
- You're not joining?
- No.

191
00:17:52,846 --> 00:17:55,781
I guess where you've been,
you can lap it up all you want.

192
00:17:55,949 --> 00:17:58,713
Well, here's to the boys
in the friendly trenches.

193
00:17:58,885 --> 00:18:00,876
Skol.

194
00:18:04,157 --> 00:18:05,954
It's a wonderfully strong vintage.

195
00:18:07,961 --> 00:18:10,794
I don't know what you're after
with me, Mr. Hallett...

196
00:18:10,964 --> 00:18:14,229
...but I will say I like the way
you're going after it.

197
00:18:14,568 --> 00:18:17,298
But I think it's only fair to warn you...

198
00:18:17,471 --> 00:18:19,701
...l've been approached
from every angle...

199
00:18:19,873 --> 00:18:24,003
...including this one of "let's get
her loaded and see what happens."

200
00:18:24,511 --> 00:18:26,672
I don't doubt it.

201
00:18:27,581 --> 00:18:31,881
Due to some kind of chemicals
in my makeup, I guess...

202
00:18:32,052 --> 00:18:36,352
...they always run out of money before
they ever find out what happens.

203
00:18:36,523 --> 00:18:39,083
Well, thank you for telling me.

204
00:18:40,093 --> 00:18:45,360
Now, to get back to this yachting trip
that you took with Pete.

205
00:18:45,532 --> 00:18:48,592
Wasn't this boat owned
by Mr. Ben Costain?

206
00:18:48,769 --> 00:18:50,930
- It was owned by somebody.
- Yes, of course.

207
00:18:51,104 --> 00:18:53,698
It was a big boat.
I can't imagine it being unowned.

208
00:18:53,874 --> 00:18:57,901
But Costain owned it, and you were
on it when it went to the West Indies.

209
00:18:58,245 --> 00:19:00,941
Since when is trips
on yachts illegal?

210
00:19:01,114 --> 00:19:03,810
I told you, we're not accusing you
of anything.

211
00:19:03,984 --> 00:19:05,451
It's Ben Costain we're after.

212
00:19:05,619 --> 00:19:08,713
How many guys have already gone
after that person...

213
00:19:08,889 --> 00:19:11,084
...and ended up 12 feet under?

214
00:19:11,258 --> 00:19:14,056
I think the government has
a way to finally get him...

215
00:19:14,227 --> 00:19:16,422
...if we can get some help from you.

216
00:19:16,596 --> 00:19:17,858
Me?

217
00:19:18,031 --> 00:19:23,333
He didn't notice if I had three heads
or four that whole delightful cruise.

218
00:19:23,503 --> 00:19:27,234
Now, on this trip
to the West Indies...

219
00:19:27,407 --> 00:19:30,342
...the boat put in
to several islands, didn't it?

220
00:19:30,510 --> 00:19:33,001
- Did it?
- You know it did. Why?

221
00:19:33,180 --> 00:19:35,910
I don't know. I took it Mr. Costain
was interested...

222
00:19:36,083 --> 00:19:37,846
...in some untamed natives perhaps.

223
00:19:38,018 --> 00:19:43,081
And at one of these islands,
this man came aboard the yacht.

224
00:19:43,256 --> 00:19:45,451
Signor Maracelli.

225
00:19:45,625 --> 00:19:49,652
The Italian garden expert. He taught
me to say his name himself.

226
00:19:49,830 --> 00:19:52,390
Did you notice how long
he stayed aboard?

227
00:19:52,566 --> 00:19:56,434
Sure. Until we let him off one night,
near Florida someplace.

228
00:19:56,603 --> 00:19:58,093
For what reason?

229
00:19:58,271 --> 00:20:01,536
Oh, he was looking
for some night-blooming wildlife.

230
00:20:01,708 --> 00:20:03,869
Did he come back to the yacht?

231
00:20:04,044 --> 00:20:09,380
They told us the signor
was destroyed in the swamp.

232
00:20:10,217 --> 00:20:12,651
These are people that you
don't doubt their word.

233
00:20:12,819 --> 00:20:14,810
When they say somebody's
in the swamp...

234
00:20:14,988 --> 00:20:16,580
...you don't ask for wet shoes.

235
00:20:16,757 --> 00:20:18,054
Yes.

236
00:20:18,225 --> 00:20:23,390
Well, Signor Maracelli's real name
happens to be Frank Domano...

237
00:20:23,563 --> 00:20:26,964
...one of the bosses of the Mafia.
- I thought he'd get someplace.

238
00:20:27,134 --> 00:20:30,729
He's been involved in quite a few
murders since he was destroyed.

239
00:20:31,404 --> 00:20:34,168
And by smuggling a man
of this kind into the country...

240
